tweet: In Maine for example, the Secretary of State has to pre-approve changes to polling place locations to make sure the changes are fair and accessible to voters.  Makes sense, right?This is one of the big federal debates right now and why #JohnLewisVotingRightsAct is so important.

name: Shenna Bellows
tweet: voter suppression.  The idea is that the Justice Dept should be able to stop changes to voting laws that will harm voters BEFORE they go into effect instead of just being able to sue after the fact when it’s too late. #mepolitics

name: Shenna Bellows
tweet: The John Lewis Voting Rights Act restores “pre-clearance” protections contained in the Voting Rights Act legislation that passed unanimously in 2006 but then were gutted by the Supreme Court.  The word itself may be boring but the substance really matters in terms of checks on

name: Shenna Bellows
tweet: For what it’s worth pre-clearance, the requirement that states with histories of voter suppression submit voting changes to feds, worked well before gutted by Supreme Court.  Section 2 of Voting Rights Act won’t stop the travesty that’s happening right now in Texas election.
